  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Argentina's private healthcare rivals developed countries. Buenos Aires hospitals would be excellent by US or European standards, and medical costs are significantly lower. Understanding the system helps maximize both local resources and international insurance.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Top Buenos Aires hospitals</strong> include Hospital Alemán (German Hospital), Hospital Italiano, Hospital Británico, and Sanatorio Mater Dei. These facilities have modern equipment, internationally trained doctors, and quality comparable to major US academic medical centers. Most have patient coordination services for international patients.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Medical training</strong> in Argentina is excellent. Many doctors train at University of Buenos Aires medical school—one of Latin America's best—and complete fellowships in the US or Europe. English is common among specialists in major hospitals, though basic Spanish helps for administrative matters.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Specialist availability:</strong> Buenos Aires has specialists across all fields, including subspecialties that might be scarce in smaller Latin American countries. Oncology, cardiology, neurology, and other complex specialties are available locally. Appointment wait times are typically shorter than in the US.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Regional healthcare:</strong> Quality decreases outside Buenos Aires, though Córdoba and Mendoza have adequate private hospitals. Smaller cities and rural areas require travel to major centers. For serious conditions, Buenos Aires remains the destination—but most retirees live there anyway.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Pharmacies are abundant and medications affordable. Many drugs available only by prescription in the US are over-the-counter in Argentina. However, some US brands aren't available—bring documentation of your prescriptions to find equivalent local options.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Argentina offers excellent value, particularly given the quality of life. Currency fluctuations create both opportunity and complexity—when the peso weakens (often), your dollar income buys more. Planning should account for this variability.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from $2,000-3,500 depending on lifestyle and currency conditions. Buenos Aires comfortable retirement runs $2,400-3,500; Mendoza or Córdoba can achieve similar lifestyle for $1,800-2,600.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Currency strategy matters.</strong> Argentina has multiple exchange rates—official, "blue" (parallel), and others. Accessing the best rates for your dollar income can effectively reduce costs 20-40%. Many retirees use services like Western Union or Wise to optimize transfers. Currency regulations change frequently—stay informed.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare cost comparison:</strong> International insurance costs ($370-750/month) are similar to other destinations. Argentine prepaga ($200-500/month) offers a local alternative for daily care. The combination of excellent local healthcare at modest cost plus international backup provides strong protection at reasonable total expense.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Lifestyle value:</strong> Your dollar buys more lifestyle in Argentina than most places. Domestic help, dining out, wine, cultural events—these are accessible to middle-class retirees in Argentina but luxury expenses elsewhere. This lifestyle inflation should be budgeted, but it's enjoyable inflation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Argentina economically stable enough for retirement?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Argentina has chronic economic volatility—inflation, currency controls, and periodic crises. However, retirees with dollar-denominated income are somewhat insulated and often benefit from peso weakness. Keeping savings in dollars outside Argentina provides security.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How good is English in Argentine healthcare?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Better than most Latin American countries. Many doctors in Buenos Aires' top hospitals speak English, especially specialists. Hospital patient coordination offices often have English-speaking staff. Basic Spanish still helps significantly for administrative matters.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can Argentine prepaga replace international insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">For residents who stay in Argentina, prepaga provides excellent coverage at lower cost. However, it doesn't cover travel, has no evacuation benefits, and may exclude pre-existing conditions. Many retirees use prepaga plus lighter international coverage as a balance.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What about Buenos Aires winters?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Buenos Aires winters (June-August) are mild—temperatures rarely below 40°F—but buildings often lack central heating, making interiors feel cold. Many retirees become "snowbirds" in reverse, spending Argentine winter in warmer locations or the Northern Hemisphere summer.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Buenos Aires safe?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Generally yes, with normal urban precautions. Petty theft and pickpocketing occur in tourist areas. Violent crime against foreigners is rare in residential neighborhoods. Most retirees report feeling safe in Palermo, Recoleta, Belgrano, and similar neighborhoods.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How fast can I get Argentine citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Just 2 years of legal residence—one of the world's fastest paths. Argentina allows dual citizenship, so you don't sacrifice your original nationality. Argentine citizenship provides EU visa-free travel and serves as a valuable backup passport.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Argentina Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers experienced with retirees in Argentina. Direct billing at Buenos Aires' excellent hospitals makes care seamless."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
